    external_code, authors, organization, uia_region, selected,
    created_at
) VALUES (
    'Future Edu Space(FES) Prototype',
    'The Future Edu Space (FES) classroom has been envisaged to promote and inspire the creation of creative, sustainable, and comfortable educational spaces. It has been designed to transform learning experiences, considering many Chilean schools in the Bio-Bío region have deficient infrastructure that critically affects the student community. 

FES used an interdisciplinary approach, linking areas as diverse as architecture, design, education, and engineering. Public and private entities contributed to specific solutions, with the region’s key actors involved In a highly participative process. Teachers, principals, and school boards took part, giving their vision for future classrooms. Psychologists, educators, and specialists in pedagogical innovation provided guidelines about how the space had to foster 21st-century skills. The resulting space acts as a mediator between teaching practices and student learning, with the potential to develop creative and innovative skills while stimulating active participation, interaction, and communication. 

This prototype has a demonstrational role for the region’s architecture and design offices, wood companies, and builders about schools and technology transfer. It is a result of the project, “Future Edu Space: Generation of Technological Capacities to Build State-of-the-art Sustainable Educational Space from the Biobío Region”, an initiative financed by the Bio-Bío Regional Government’s Innovation for Competitivity Fund (FIC-R). The Future Edu Space (FES) prototype is an educational space that combines flexibility, adaptability, and variety in its use. Its design was developed based on interdisciplinary and collaborative work involving actors from education, design, architecture, construction, and wood industrialization. The BIM method was used throughout the design process, combined with virtual reality tools.

To break with the traditional classroom layout, it has been designed using a square neutral-style floor plan, which allows using the classroom in different senses and creating multiple educational scenarios. It has a total surface area of 100m2, with a central area of 70m2 for 35 students.

Its structure comprises two active sidewalls to support the pedagogical activities. One holds furniture for individual learning activities, and the other, which can also store furniture, has a large interactive board. It also has an acoustic wall that folds inward to extend activities to an adjoining space. The final wall is glazed, connecting with the outside to take pedagogical activities further still.
Passive strategies are included to generate appropriate environmental conditions: temperature (thermal envelope), air quality (crossed ventilation), acoustics (foldable acoustic doors and partition), and daylight (lucarnes and view windows).

It considers the design of flexible furniture to provide an easily adjusted multipurpose learning space. For example, changing from a presentation space to one for participation or group work.

FES is designed with a wooden prefabricated system, to foster wood-based architecture in the education area. The geometry is obtained from a construction technology capacity and modulation process. A 1.2m x 3m CLT (Cross Laminated Timber) module, which is easy to transport and meets the requirements of the architectural space, is used for the sidewalls using the manufacturing skills of local wood companies.

The educational space’s structure comprises CLT frames that form part of the active sidewalls, with GLT (Glued Laminated Timber) beams for the ceiling’s caisson structure. CLT wall braces are placed between the frames. The walls do not have an indoor coating, leaving the same CLT pine wall. The outdoor covering is a thermally modified tongue and groove.

The FES prototype is conceived as a unitary system that can be repeated and joined together to generate new options. Three variants are proposed: EDU SPACE FRONT, EDU SPACE NEXT, and EDU SPACE UP. These are organized by two main elements: the essential indoor space module, and an independent ring surrounding it, forming an intermediate space. The prototype and its variants inspire projecting and building new ways of developing school architecture.',
    'Concepción, Region del Bio-Bio, Chile',
    NULL,
    NULL,
    'completed', 'architectural', 'public',
    (SELECT id FROM "user" WHERE email = 'import@uia.archi'),
    'IFF12', 'Beatriz Piderit (FES Project Director), Maureen Trebilcock (FES Project Coordinator), Alejandra Bancalari (Design Architect), Valentina Chandia (Design Architect), Carlos Coronado (Design Architect), Javiera Leighton  (editor)', 'Univeridad del Bio-Bio, Concepción, Chile', 'Region 3', true,
    NOW()
);

