) VALUES (
    'Sustainable Rural Development Program: One University One Village',
    'The One University One Village (1U1V) Initiative was launched by Prof. Edward NG and Dr. Li WAN at The Chinese University of Hong Kong (CUHK) in 2014. It aspires to bring together the expertise, knowledge and human resources of “a university” to improve the livelihood of “a village” and its needy villagers in a strategic, systematic and sustainable manner. In 2015, 1U1V team conducted a post-earthquake reconstruction project in Yunnan, China to demonstrate the use of “high-science-low-technology” strategies with the “local materials, local labour, and local technology” principle of rural construction, and to encourage endogenous development in rural China. The project and the holistic strategy behand it creatively mended the environmental, economic, and social sustainable development of poor rural areas. Since 2017, the team started to scale up the work, and to continue the work more systematically, with the building of the Terra Centre in Kunming as the working base in China to research, promote, train and knowledge transfer. With funding support from the Chan Cheung Mun Chung Charitable Fund, 60 more village houses have been rebuilt and more than 70 houses are under construction in Southwest China. Sustainable rural development is a significant issue in China, which has more than 40% of its population living in rural areas. The development of poor rural areas in mountainous regions of Southwest China has been relatively slow and unsustainable. The crucial support that poor rural areas of China require is not only funding but also innovative ideas and systematic strategies. Rammed earth construction has a long history in China. Raw earth is the main material used in traditional architecture because it is inexpensive, accessible and exhibits remarkable thermal performance. However, under the impact of urbanization, rural residents tend to think that earthen buildings are associated to poverty and backwardness. Moreover, improving the seismic performance of earth buildings is a big challenge since many of them are located in earthquake-prone areas. To provide a suitable and sustainable solution for rural reconstruction in Southwest China, our team explores the research and innovates rammed earth building technology to provide a safe, economical, simple, and sustainable reconstruction strategy that the rural residents can afford, own, and disseminate.
To ensure systematic and sustainable rural reconstruction work with innovative ideas, scientific research is essential to understand the context, identify the problem, and find a proper solution. To empower the rural residents and encourage endogenous development, “high-science-low-technology” strategies and “local labour, local materials, and local technology” principle was applied in poor rural areas in Southwest China. Instead of promoting the benefits of imported brick and concrete, our team determined whether the shortfalls of traditional rammed earth technology and the fragility of village life could be addressed in situ. The implementation of this strategy was a simple step in rebuilding the lives of the people. Since 2014, our team has started to build rural houses to demonstrate a comprehensive and systematic construction system and resulting substantially high building quality. Meanwhile, the residents were empowered through the demonstration projects with craftsman training and co-construction. Through this long-term cooperation and learning-by-doing process, we established mutual trust with the villagers and convinced them that the innovative, anti-seismic rammed earth building was a good solution. 
Our rural programme provides an interdisciplinary, innovative and sustainable solution for poor rural areas in China. This solution has been generated by multidisciplinary partnerships and networking platforms. We also hope this knowledge database can also inspire and lead the work of the local governments and other NGOs in China and other underprivileged areas in less-developed countries, and eventually create a knowledge value chain that helps build a better future for rural communities around the world. More than 60 village houses have been rebuilt and more than 70 houses are under construction in Southwest China. More than 6 villager craftsman construction teams (including a women construction team) were established. Moreover, the innovative rammed earth building technology can be replicated for the improvement of poor rural areas where there are similar natural and social conditions to those in the poor rural areas of Southwest China, for example, in the rural regions of Nepal and India.',
    'Southwest rural China',
