    'Terra Centre',
    'Through the cooperation with Kunming University of Science and Technology (KUST), One University One Village team have improved the construction technology and seismic performance of the earth construction in Southwest rural China. In order to carry out long-term artisans training, to provide space for conducting experiments, research and practical study, and to showcase the technologies and achievements of new seismic earth construction, the 1U1V team built the Terra Centre in KUST campus with funding support from the Chan Cheung Mun Chung Charitable Fund.
The project design is highly based on the local climate condition of Kunming. Appropriate passive design strategies guaranteed low operating energy consumption. All the materials used in the wall are natural materials. No industrial stabilizers were added in the earth wall. The wall is 100% recyclable, degradable, and pollution free. 
The Terra Centre is not only a building but a research and education tool. The team trained and employed villagers to build the Terra Centre and thus transfer to them a way to make their livings economically later. The result verified an appropriated solution of the local reconstruction that provides references for national rural construction policies and earth building seismic standards. Research shows that socioeconomic value is crucial in sustainable rural development. The environmental load of vernacular houses in poor rural areas is low already. The key issue is how to improve the safety, quality and dignity of the living environment without adding substantial environmental load. Earth building has a very long history in China. Terra Center as a research centre for earthen architecture and rural sustainable development, applied “high-science and low-technology” strategy with “local materials, local labour and local technology” principle to encourage endogenous and sustainable development in poor rural areas in China.
    The building design is highly based on local climate condition so that proper passive design strategies can be selected. Kunming has a moderate climate with abundant sunshine and large temperature difference between day and night. With good thermal mass, rammed earth wall is a very suitable material. We designed a semi-outdoor space with top lighting in the middle of the building to provide a comfortable multifunctional space for multiple training and academic activities. Passive design strategies including passive solar heating, natural ventilation, and shading guaranteed high indoor environmental quality and low operating energy consumption. No active cooling and heating equipment has been used in this project.
    To minimize the impact to the local environment, 89% of the building materials (by weight) are local natural materials (raw earth, gravel, sand, and bamboo). No industrial stabilizer was added to the wall, i.e., the wall is 100% recyclable and pollution-free. The roof structure is made of bamboo that is a fast-growing material with low embodied energy. No decoration material was used on the building façade and interior walls. Industrial materials, such as cement and steel, are limited and efficiently used in key structural parts to ensure building safety and building environmental quality.
    We meet the safety needs of people by improving the building seismic performance. To improve wall strength and reduce cracks, we analyzed the basic properties of the soil and optimized the proportion by adding gravel and sand. The air compressed rammers and the aluminum alloy formwork are applied to Improving the compressive strength of the wall. In terms of structural design, reinforced concrete tie columns, ring beams, foundation and floor slabs are applied to enhance the structural integrity. The result of mechanical property tests and shaking table tests corroborates that the seismic performance of the rammed earth building significantly is improved, thereby meeting the local seismic codes perfectly.
The Terra Centre is not only a building but a research and education tool. We trained and employed villagers to build the Terra Centre and thus transfer to them a way to make their livings economically later. 33 villagers (including 5 women) joined this project and passed the craftsmen training. The project changed the attitude of the villagers towards rammed earth buildings. They became interested in switching back from their brick-concrete houses because the project protected their local traditional construction method and lifestyle. The project result provides references for national rural construction policies and earth building seismic standards.',
    'Kunming，China',
    1328.5,
