) VALUES (
    'Oil mill & cannery of Segermès - Zaghouan / Tunisia',
    'The oil mill & cannery project is a concept fully integrated into the site, from picking to bottling and labeling. It’s also an attempt to rehabilitate a fringe of territory by infusing new productive energy. An energy that creates values, jobs and well-being.
Respecting the waxworks of organic farming, the olive growing complex now allows the production of very high-quality organic olive oil following a process fully integrated into the site. It employs around 100 men and women during the production phases. Modern technologies allow the use of local resources and place sustainability at the heart of all agricultural and business activities.
Olive cultivation plays an essential role in the social and economic life of Tunisia and represents around 15% of the total value of final agricultural production. In addition, the olive sector represents the direct or indirect livelihood of more than 1 million people.
Rural Tunisian women participate very actively in the picking of olive trees; these jobs, although seasonal, provide rural families with very appreciable annual income which generally contributes to financing children''s education ...
Today, agricultural products from the Segermès estate stand out for their high quality both on the Tunisian market and internationally. Rewarded with numerous distinctions on a worldwide scale. Route & confluence: The establishment of the project emanates from a territorial position. The chosen location maintains a privileged dialogue with a water reservoir as well as a basilica from the Byzantine period. The project is part of the logic of a confluence, an emergence built by the directional multiplicity of the natural and “civilizational” components of this unique place.
A historical past: The foundations of the new building are nourished by the historical roots of the place whose Byzantine remains remain. The ground floor opens onto the landscape and overlooks the old basilica through the presence of a Forum which becomes a semi-public space for meetings and contemplation. The staging of the archaeological remains also helps to revive the historical past of the region which was previously abandoned.
The olive tree at the heart of the process: The architecture of the oil mill, resulting from the framework of the olive grove, also tells the story of the extraction process. The oil is kept in the center of the building and the volume of the silos thus constitutes a link between the two levels of the new building.',
