    'Reviving AL-Nazlah',
    'Reviving the Al-Nazlah area in Fayoum aims to create a pilot project in contexts of specificity. The valuable district incubates pottery workshops which have been producing special pots used for construction since Ancient Egyptian Civilization. Thus, the upgraded construction technique which enhanced the bonding material gluing the pots together via the help of lab experiments maintained the traditional technique. Also, new forms have been introduced for the roofing construction, which enabled the local community to explore a wider range of spans through introducing domes & vaults constructed by pots. The project was initiated by Arch. El-Setouhy with an aim to indulge the local community in a participatory process which enables the locals to learn, appreciate, create and govern their cultural product. Thus, enabling them to achieve the three pillars of sustainability for the project, social, economic and environmental sustenance.  The project has been awarded the second prize of the Baku Award in 2019, Category A, with the support of UIA for creating a sustainable environmental development nucleus that has many positive impacts on the whole region. The project was nominated to receive the Aga-Khan Award cycle 2022. Also, shortlisted in the Arab Association Award for the last cycle 2022. Concept: Develop the Nazlah area by reviving its cultural heritage and returning it to become a cultural product again that the local people can be proud of it. 
Goals:
Pilot project, give a model about improving performance and maximize benefits for areas which has different kinds of arts of their local culture over hundreds of years, that Egypt has many of it. 
Create a sustain environmental development nucleus that has many positive impacts on the whole region.
Reviving the traditional crafts that characterize the region, to protect it from extinction.
Seeking to restore the place to its former value that brought happiness to the local people, while restoring confidence in their cultural heritage.

The interlocking of the pots forms a continuous arch, which creates a load-bearing mechanism. The variations and repetition of the load-bearing elements create a variety of spaces and roof treatments. The climatic sustainability stems from the zero-waste process adopted in the construction technique. The Visitor witness a powerful environmentally friendly climatic nature in terms of adequacy of internal temperatures and also as to its coherence with the surrounding nature. The geometrical iterations in the construction of the roof, which created diffused sunlight radiations on the building added an important layer in the lower temperatures inside the buildings.  This manipulation of the roof results in less heat transfer into the internal spaces than the conventional R.C. and mud bricks construction modes. The project created a process of discovery of a heritage asset, the capitalization of the architect through a participatory methodology of a familiar practice of construction that was about to go extinct, in a contemporary mode which explores architectural aesthetical values and adventurous journeys in the spatial experiences of the Visitor center. 
Program:
-Visitor center:
Introduces the historical value of this site, which facilitates marketing issue.
Contains a number of halls. The first, displays samples and information on the various pottery products produced by the people of the region, attached to it is a hall on the tools they use in making pottery, next to a hall documenting artwork (movies and songs) that were filmed in the region.
Attached to the visitor center is a space used to sit and enjoy the beautiful scenery of the waterway.
-An exhibition for displaying and selling pottery products, consisting of three rooms attached to an open space next to the current pergola to be an extension of the products display.
-Development of workshops:
The development of new workshops that were built soon, of white limestone blocks, which are not commensurate with the nature of the place and its cultural heritage.
-Services – Landscape:
Provide a multipurpose space for different cultural and related activities.
Facilitate a secured passing way for visitors that do not interrupt that of workers.
The project is closely linked to the SDGs, and sought to achieve a set of its goals, whether in the stages of implementation or after implementation, especially the goals numbers (1-3-7-13)',
